SUMMARY: 90 Minutes of Innovation: Top Gun Meets a $2+ Billion Aviation Gam
 e-Changer 
LOCATION:The Pub
DESCRIPTION:Category: ‘Quin Chat\nPrice: Free\nAvailability: 1 spot left\
 nStatus: You are Confirmed\nEvent URL: https://members.thequinhouse.com/ev
 ents/169177\n\n1:00PM Program\, 2:30PM Networking \nTwo frontiers. One st
 age. Not to be missed. In this high-voltage edition of 90 Minutes of Innov
 ation\, flight becomes more than a metaphor — it becomes a stress test f
 or the future of AI\, defense\, climate innovation\, and human judgment it
 self.\n\nJohn Werner — venture capitalist\, Forbes AI columnist\, and In
 novation Curator at The ’Quin House — convenes an extraordinary pairin
 g you won’t see anywhere else. A real-world Top Gun who has flown 80 com
 bat missions\, 290 test missions\, and logged more than 2\,000 hours acros
 s 30 aircraft — including the F-35\, F-15\, and F-16 — operating along
 side AI in live\, high-stakes environments. And a leader helping build one
  of the most highly capitalized electric aviation companies in the world.\
 n\nFirst: Kristen Costello\n\nBuilding the Next Aviation System\n\nKristen
  Costello is a pilot and executive at Vermont-based Beta Technologies\, a 
 New England aerospace company valued at more than $2 billion and backed by
  over $1 billion from Fidelity\, Qatar Investment Authority\, Amazon’s C
 limate Pledge Fund\, GE Aerospace\, and others.\n\nBeta isn’t pitching a
  concept. It’s building a new aviation system. Founded by former Harvard
  hockey player Kyle Clark — once told not to return to Vermont because �
 ��there was nothing there” — Beta has grown into one of the most ambit
 ious aerospace companies on the planet. The company is developing all-elec
 tric aircraft for cargo\, medical logistics\, and passenger travel while s
 imultaneously constructing a nationwide charging network. It has completed
  cross-country flights\, secured major commercial and defense partnerships
 \, and is advancing through the FAA’s rigorous certification process.\n\
 nThe breakthrough isn’t just the airplane. It’s the systems thinking �
 �� aircraft\, charging infrastructure\, certification\, pilot training\, a
 nd operations built in parallel. Not incremental change\, but a redesign o
 f regional air mobility from propulsion to power grid. If it succeeds\, it
  won’t just change how we fly. It will change where flying makes sense.\
 n\nThen: Tucker “Cinco” Hamilton\n\nWhere Humans and AI Share the Cock
 pit\n\nThe evening shifts to contested airspace.\n\nRetired U.S. Air Force
  Colonel and experimental fighter test pilot Tucker “Cinco” Hamilton �
 �� former Chief of AI Test and Operations for the U.S. Air Force and Space
  Force — led the integration of AI-enabled autonomy into combat aircraft
 . He has operated at the edge\, where algorithms and humans share the cock
 pit in real-time\, high-consequence environments.\n\nHamilton brings audie
 nces inside moments few will ever experience: ejecting from a failing airc
 raft\, managing an engine fire at twice the speed of sound\, crash-landing
  a jet while fighting to keep it upright\, and flying combat missions over
  Afghanistan. For Hamilton\, AI is not theoretical. It is airborne. He has
  confronted the defining questions of our era:\n\nWhen should a machine be
  trusted?\n\nHow do you test systems that learn?\n\nWhat happens when AI e
 volves faster than doctrine?\n\nWho is accountable when autonomy acts?\n\n
 This program also marks the debut of his new book\, Unlocking the Last 20%
 \, on elite performance in an age of automation.\n\nAviation has always pr
 eviewed the future. Now it is revealing the operating system of the next c
 entury. The future is not humans replaced by machines. It is humans redesi
 gned alongside them.\n\n*This event is complimentary and reserved for memb
 ers only. Light bites and refreshments will be served.
